# Branch naming (Conventional Branches)

Use the same **type** vocabulary as [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/). Branch names must be lowercase, kebab-case, and ASCII.

## Format

```
<type>/<short-description>
```

Optional scope (use when it clarifies the area):

```
<type>/<scope>-<short-description>
```

| Part | Rules |
|------|--------|
| `type` | Required. One of: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `style`, `refactor`, `perf`, `test`, `build`, `ci`, `chore` |
| `scope` | Optional. Short area: `canvas`, `timeline`, `vault`, `copilot`, `export`, `api`, `db`, `ui` |
| `short-description` | 2–5 words, kebab-case, no spaces |

## Examples

```
feat/timeline-event-pins
fix/canvas-pin-sync
docs/collaborator-deploy-guide
ci/vercel-preview-workflow
chore/deps-next-16
refactor/vault-store-split
```

## Do not use

- `main`, `master`, `develop` (except `main` as the protected default branch)
- Vague names: `update`, `fixes`, `wip`, `test-branch`, `john-work`
- Uppercase, underscores, or slashes beyond the first: `Feat/foo`, `feat/my_branch`, `feat/foo/bar`
- Personal or date prefixes: `dinura-05-16`, `feature-123` (use ticket in commit body instead)

## Agent workflow

1. **Never** commit directly to `main`. Branch from latest `main`, then open a PR.
2. Pick `type` from the **upcoming commit’s** primary intent (same type you would use in the commit subject).
3. If the branch will hold multiple unrelated changes, split into separate branches instead of one broad name.
4. Before pushing, confirm the branch name matches this pattern; rename with `git branch -m` if needed.

## Pairing with commits

Branch type should match the **dominant** commit type on that branch. Commits on the branch still follow Conventional Commits, e.g. `feat(timeline): add ghost nodes for copilot suggestions`.
